<subSubSection pageId="91" pageNumber="92" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1436,261,432]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,290,262,288]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Etymology:</emphasis>
This species is named after its body color. The name is a combination of Latin words ‘purpura’ and ‘caeruleus’ meaning ‘purple’ and ‘blue’ respectively. Specific epithet is a noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="91" pageNumber="92" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="91.[151,1436,261,432]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,324,333,360]" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
This species is close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Medvedev" authorityYear="1993" box="[597,763,333,360]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Chaetocnema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="himalayana">
<emphasis box="[597,763,333,360]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">C. himalayana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[819,959,333,360]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jacoby, 1892 in Medvedev" authorityYear="2001" box="[819,955,333,360]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Chaetocnema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="duvivieri">C. duvivieri</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
It may be distinguished by the shorter antennae, unique frontal ridge decorated with wrinkles and dark purple blue dorsum. It is also close to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chujo" authorityYear="1965" box="[1265,1429,370,396]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Chaetocnema" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="91" pageNumber="92" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taiwanensis">
<emphasis box="[1265,1429,370,396]" italics="true" pageId="91" pageNumber="92">C. taiwanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, however, they are entirely different in coloration.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
